.TH "runsvdir" "8" 
.SH NAME
runsvdir \- starts and monitors a collection of runsv(8) processes
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]runsvdir\f[R] [\-P] \f[I]dir\f[R] [ \f[I]log\f[R] ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[I]dir\f[R] must be a directory.
\f[I]log\f[R] is a space holder for a readproctitle log, and must be at
least seven characters long or absent.
.PP
\f[B]runsvdir\f[R] starts a \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process for each
subdirectory, or symlink to a directory, in the services directory
\f[I]dir\f[R], up to a limit of 1000 subdirectories, and restarts a
\f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process if it terminates.
\f[B]runsvdir\f[R] skips subdirectory names starting with dots.
\f[B]runsv\f[R](8) must be in \f[B]runsvdir\f[R]\[aq]s PATH.
.PP
At least every five seconds \f[B]runsvdir\f[R] checks whether the time
of last modification, the inode, or the device, of the services
directory \f[I]dir\f[R] has changed.
If so, it re\-scans the service directory, and if it sees a new
subdirectory, or new symlink to a directory, in \f[I]dir\f[R], it starts
a new \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process; if \f[B]runsvdir\f[R] sees a
subdirectory being removed that was previously there, it sends the
corresponding \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process a TERM signal, stops monitoring
this process, and so does not restart the \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process if
it exits.
.PP
If the \f[I]log\f[R] argument is given to \f[B]runsvdir\f[R], all output
to standard error is redirected to this \f[I]log\f[R], which is similar
to the daemontools\[aq] \f[B]readproctitle\f[R] log.
To see the most recent error messages, use a process\-listing tool such
as \f[B]ps\f[R](1).
\f[B]runsvdir\f[R] writes a dot to the readproctitle log every 15
minutes so that old error messages expire.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-P\f[R]
use \f[B]setsid\f[R](2) to run each \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process in a new
session and separate process group.
.SH SIGNALS
If \f[B]runsvdir\f[R] receives a TERM signal, it exits with 0
immediately.
.PP
If \f[B]runsvdir\f[R] receives a HUP signal, it sends a TERM signal to
each \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process it is monitoring and then exits with
111.
.SH SEE ALSO
sv(8), runsv(8), runsvchdir(8), runit(8), runit\-init(8), chpst(8),
svlogd(8), setsid(2)
.PP
